SIMPLE: gyre
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gyre
<hw>Gyre</hw> <pr>(j⟦imac⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>gyrus</ets>, Gr. <grk>gy^ros</grk>, cf. <grk>gyro`s</grk>
round.]</ety> <def>A circular motion, or a circle described by a moving
body; a turn or revolution; a circuit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Quick and more quick he spins in giddy <qex>gyres</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Still expanding and ascending <qex>gyres</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs.
Browning. </qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gyre</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gyre
<hw>Gyre</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>gyrer</ets>,
<ets>girer</ets>. See <er>Gyrate</er>.]</ety> <def>To turn round; to
gyrate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au>
<au>Drayton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gyreful</ent>⟦br⟧
